Each Phase II applicant will be required to provide information for the Small
Business Administration Tech-Net Database System. See the section above under SBIR
entitled "Phase II Data Collection Requirement" for more
information.</p>

<p class=MsoPlainText><a name="_Toc30479238"></a><a name="_Toc29274007"><b><font
size=2 face=Arial><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold'>Animal
Studies</span></font></b></a><b><span style='font-weight:bold'>.</span></b> The
Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) verification of approval of
proposed research involving Vertebrate Animals is not required at the time of
application. It may be submitted with the application or in a "just-in-time"
fashion prior to award (as is now permitted for IRB approval). Additional
information is available from the following NIH Guide Notice: <span
class=MsoHyperlink><u><font color=blue><a
href="http://grants2.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-02-064.html">http://grants2.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-02-064.html</a></font></u></span>.
As part of the review process, the Scientific Review Group will continue to
address the adequacy of animal usage and protection in applications; however,
verification of IACUC review and approval may be submitted just prior to award.
Therefore, be sure to address the points under "Vertebrate Animals"
in your Research Plan.&nbsp; </p>

<p class=MsoPlainText><font size=2 face=Arial><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></font></p>

<p class=MsoPlainText><b><font size=2 face=Arial><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
font-weight:bold'>Specific PHS 398 Instructions included <i><span
style='font-style:italic'>within</span></i> the Solicitation.</span></font></b>
This past year, many of you have expressed a bit of ... shall we say...frustration
in using the PHS 398 instructions, most of which related to too many cross-references
and links within the document rather than providing the specific instruction.&nbsp;
Taking these comments into consideration, and thinking about the FAQs that I
received, we decided this year to INCLUDE the specific instructions for
completing the PHS 398 forms WITHIN the Omnibus Solicitation. I hope the
instructions are easier to follow.</p>

<h3><b><font size=2 face=Arial><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Clarification of
Budget Instructions.</span></font></b><font size=2><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
font-weight:normal'> Most of the questions I get relate to preparation of your
budget. This year, the budget instructions have been extensively rewritten. &nbsp;This
section is now divided into two parts: &nbsp;(1) Modular (for those
applications requesting $100,000 or less in total costs) and (2) Non-Modular
(for those applications requesting more than $100,000 in total costs). &nbsp;These
sections are then classified by program (SBIR and STTR). &nbsp;For those
applications requesting multiple years of support, the Non-Modular Section has
been classified even further to separate the budget information required for
the "Initial Budget Period" and the "Entire Proposed Period
of Support." A summary chart of the necessary forms for each is included
at the beginning of the Budget Instructions. &nbsp;Use this chart to assure
that you have submitted the correct forms appropriate to your specific type of
application.</span></font></h3>

<p class=MsoPlainText><font size=2 face=Arial><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Sample
budgets now available!!<b><span style='font-weight:bold'> To assist in the
development of your budget, check out the sample budgets for modular and non-modular
SBIR/STTR applications. </span></b>Remember, if you requesting a budget/project
period that deviates from the guidelines, you are strongly encouraged to discuss
intent with Program staff prior to submission and you MUST justify in your
application the need to exceed the guidelines. </span></font></p>

